{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624432"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:18:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:18:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16899"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16899"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.69,0.14,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67594"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9589"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16899"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53046"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"7646"},{"type":"tags","id":"10959"},{"type":"tags","id":"11135"},{"type":"tags","id":"12388"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22647"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67594"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA genetic counsellor is discussing chromosomal abnormalities with a couple planning pregnancy. The discussion turns to Edwards syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the genetic basis of Edwards syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deletion of chromosome 18","Presence of three copies of chromosome 18","Partial deletion of chromosome 18q","Presence of four copies of chromosome 18","Translocation between chromosomes 18 and 21"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEdwards syndrome is characterised by the \u003Cstrong\u003Epresence of three copies of chromosome 18\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs most commonly due to nondisjunction during maternal meiosis I, resulting in an extra copy of chromosome 18 in the embryo.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeletion of chromosome 18\u003C/strong\u003E - This would result in monosomy 18, which is typically lethal in early embryonic development\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranslocation between chromosomes 18 and 21\u003C/strong\u003E - While chromosomal translocations can occur, they are not the primary mechanism for Edwards syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresence of four copies of chromosome 18\u003C/strong\u003E - This would be tetrasomy 18, which is extremely rare and typically incompatible with life\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial deletion of chromosome 18q\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes 18q deletion syndrome, a different chromosomal disorder\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEdwards syndrome is characterised by low birth weight, microcephaly, micrognathia, clenched fists with overlapping fingers, rocker-bottom feet, and severe developmental delay. Most affected infants have congenital heart defects and other internal organ abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk of Edwards syndrome increases with maternal age, similar to other trisomy conditions. Most affected pregnancies result in miscarriage, and those that survive to term have severe developmental abnormalities. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe prognosis is poor, with only 5-10% of affected infants surviving beyond their first year of life due to the severity of their congenital abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Edwards syndrome (trisomy 18) is characterised by the presence of an extra copy of chromosome 18.","Most cases of Edwards syndrome result from nondisjunction during meiosis, typically maternal meiosis I.","The risk of Edwards syndrome increases with maternal age.","Edwards syndrome has a poor prognosis with most affected infants dying within the first year of life."],"references":["Cereda A, Carey JC. The trisomy 18 syndrome. Orphanet Journal of Rare Diseases. 2012;7(1):81. Available at: https://ojrd.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/1750-1172-7-81"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53046"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16899"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53046"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T21:23:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T21:24:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9589"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67594"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"up